My Review:
Man, this made me feel so good.

It was such an enjoyable reading, specially the second half. It's been a while since a book made me externalize my reactions; I laughed out loud, I got (very) excited everytime Seth and Nick would do . anything and I tried my best to hold back tears. I really loved it.

The first half was a bit hard to go through, sometimes I'd jokingly ask myself if this book was adhd-friendly. It wasn't because it was boring, but because I just finished a fantasy book so going from killing monsters to seeing a kid being obsessed with superheroes and not that much happening was a change, but a lovely one once I got used to it.

I think what I can most highlight about this book is its character building. Nick is hilarious and self aware and I loved his relationship with his dad so much. Nick very similar to me and I loved sending my friend quotes of him I could relate to.

I would love to see more of Jazz and Gabby because god those little lesbians stole my entire heart. Jazz's so smart and strong and Gabby is so caring and responsible, they truly make the perfect pair and are on their way to be one of my favorite book couples.

I laughed so much when the author pointed how similar Owen is to Harry Osborn, I was thinking the exact same thing! But I truly hope Owen gets a redemption, my favorite moments of him was when his mask slipped.

and Seth. Nice little Seth. God I love him SO much he's easily becoming one of my favorite book characters he's truly the best person there is and he was so cute crushing on Nick i swear to god I just want to kiss him on the cheek (platonically). Also he's the strongest character in the history of books. Imagine your crush making a self insert slightly horny fanfic of your mortal enemy who BY THE WAY is also making out with your crush and having to BETA READ THAT !!! how is seth still sane

Anyways I should stop on my Seth loving rant. I can't wait to read the second book! I heard the copaganda will stop, which is really good because it was very annoying and I am very curious about how Nick will find out about his powers and how that will affect his relationship with his dad and even his mom.

4.5/5 maybe :)? very fun and made me feel really good.

My Review:
Was experiencing reader's block and this took me out of it! I needed something light and entertaining and this was just it. It's so much better than the movie and it made me love all the characters a lot more. The movie is missing a lot of explanations of why the characters act the way they do, and it changes stuff that are essential for a character's development. I liked this a lot more.

About the book itself, I loved the different styles of writing of each character. At first I was scared I'd get confused, but the great writing made me realize who was narrating according to each character's distinct writing. There's nothing I loved more about the book than the narration of the biggest moments for Lemonade Mouth, which are not narrated through their eyes, but through the witnesses' eyes.

I really recommend it if you're looking for something light and fun.

Lo mismo con la muerte de Alejandro, Alejandro era algo que ella guardaba de su otra vida y que esperaba a verlo para volver a lo que era antes de la Interperie, pero María se entera que lo matan y se queda como "Ah, bue, que pena. Bueno entonces...." Señor Pedro Mairal me tuve que comer 800 menciones de Alejandro para éste momento.

La historia no tiene mucha continuidad, y los capítulos están cortados de una forma para que no te des cuenta. Entiendo que deben representar las diferentes Marías, pero parece una colección de cuentos.

¿Por qué el final abierto encima? No sólamente esto, sino que el capítulo final se siente bastante apresurado. Es una combinación de bastantes coincidencias inexplicables. Ah, mirá vos, justo es el edificio que trabajaba, justo aparece Bairos, justo la deja vivir por razones que no entendemos en lo absoluto, justo aparece Suárez muerto, justo tiene el vestido, ¿Y todo eso, más el final, en un capítulo? Es cómo si el autor no sabía cómo terminar el libro.

En los puntos buenos, pre Martín Fierro fue bastante interesante. Especialmente los capítulos del Hospital y el Bar. La crítica a aquellas personas que viven por la televisión estuvo increíble, por eso la primera mitad del libro se llevó el premio. La segunda... eh, medio cualquier cosa.

Gente ha sacado mejores fanfics que ésto.

My Review:
"Because I want everybody in the audience to hear you" GO KING GO!!

I liked The Sea of Monsters a lot more than the The Lightning Thief! Not that The Lighting Thief was bad, it was very much enjoyable, but since this one focused in one goal (getting the Fleece) it was much lighter and easier to go through.

Not only that, but it was much happier than the first one. You can see how much Annabeth and Percy love each other, and seeing Percy grow and accept his brother was just as adorable as Tyson himself. While Grover didn't play as much of a part in this book compared to the past one, the story of this book completely revolves around him and I loved how it's connected with The Lighting Thief. I didn't thought Grover's quest would be a big plot point, but I'm glad that it was. The character development of this book was exceptional, specially for Annabeth. We only get to see her through Percy's eyes, but in this book we got a little of her own perspective as well. It was great.

The plot twists improved a lot compared to the past book. They were all enjoyable and made sense. Luckily, most did not revealed too much information, almost none at all, making me curious of the next book.

My biggest and most current complain through both books was the same: Luke. You could remove him out or just replace him with a random person or Kronos himself and the plot would still make sense. He appears at the beginning to do... nothing. Just show you the coffin, which would definitely have a big impact on the future but it still isn't directly related to him (meaning anyone could've shown the coffin), and then he returns in the end (an eye rolling decision, by the way) to do. nothing again. Not even that, in the final battle with him, Rick decides to pull a Deus ex Machina with Chiron. You know, just the most infuriating trope there is. Dude just... appears out of nowhere. That chapter pissed me off to be honest....

But it luckily it didn't forbid me to still enjoy the other parts of the books! I got plenty of good laughs and a great time reading it. I'll definitely re-read it one day.

4.5/5 stars.

My Review:
So, the first thing I thought when I first opened the book was the narration, first person in the present. Now, I'm used to reading books with omniscient narrators, even if it's overused, it's my favorite type of narration, so I wasn't sure if I'd like the writing of the book. I didn't, and I still don't, think it was the best choice for narrating. Since then my follow-up thought was, how would any of them have done it if we're reading their thoughts as they go by....? Boom, four suspects down and I had barely started the book.

Maybe it'd have been better first person in the past, people can lie there, people can't lie to their own thoughts immediately and unconsciously.

I did liked, though, Addy's character. As a person who's most similar to Brownyn, but not as half as smart as her, I always wondered how people like Addy are in their daily lives, outside of school. At first, it was just what I expected, but once Jake brokes up with her is where she really gets interesting. She was the best character in my opinion and the highlight of the book.

Cooper was ok, I felt bad for him, but before the gay announcement I was getting tired of baseball talk. He didn't really give much to the plot if I'm being honest, just the token gay character I guess...?

Brownyn.... it seemed like Brownyn was a bit difficult? I really loved whenever she wasn't narrating her moments with Nate, when she had her smart moments and when she talked about how much she loved her sister. But when she was narrating Nate... she felt out of character sometimes. Like when she was at the mall with Nate and he got mad (for something that, in my opinion, Brownyn was right) and she immediately asked him to forgive her...? I don't know, it wouldn't seem like Brownyn would've done that. (By the way the criminal and the brain dating plot... I don't know if the cliché was on purpose or not). Also whenever she talked about cheating in chemistry I felt like throwing up, I know it was a big deal for her but come on! I accepted it at the beginning because we hadn't reached the character development yet, but once we did, she still acted like it was worse than murder or something. It was annoying, ngl.

I liked Nate. It was obvious he didn't do it (without counting the narration type) because he didn't cared enough about Simon when he was alive. As much of a cliché it is, I like the good heart criminal who just wants to maintain himself. On the opposite from Brownyn, his narrations about her were heartwarming and on point. However whenever he believed he was cooler than what he was... like that narration on the juvenile... yeah, I've never cringed so hard, but he was probably the second best character of the book.

When 4Chan came to question i actually laughed. I don't know why, but everytime it's mentioned I can't take it seriously.

And for the lovely plot twist... Simon was depressed and killed himself! Dragging his classmates around, his best friend, and his ex friend, who was more than happy to help.

I don't know why, I hated it. I'm a very picky person with endings, I know they're hard to do, but I always expect the best from a writer. The ending of a book can either make me like the book a lot, even if the development sucked, or dislike it a lot, even if the development was good. That was an exaggeration, I don't dislike this book but it did disappoint me. Yes, there was some clues about it (like 4Chan, but again, I couldn't take it seriously) that you could only connect knowing who did it, but the fact we spent the entire time looking for the killer to find out he's dead....? I don't know, it feels anti-climatic, and, not going to lie, I hated how depression was portrayed here. Like if them being depressed would mean something, it meant something for Simon, yes, but it wasn't depression that led him to that, it was his twisted head. The trope that depressed people kill themselves as a revenge is already done by 13 reasons why and it's harmful as fuck, please stop. I also disliked Jake as a last minute villain. He was entertaining, let's say, but appeared at the last second and it was kind of random. Tho, maybe this would have hit harder if I thought of this book as a story of how these four teenagers' lives, with different types of secrets, gets twisted after they witness a murder (or a suicide), rather than think of it as story of finding the killer, because at the end of the day I don't think that was the highlight of the book, but how their lives change after being suspects, and I know that's probably what the writer intended, specially with making Simon "the killer", but since the book was promoted in a different way, I couldn't enjoyed it as much as I want to.

At the end of the day, this is a personal review, mostly how the book made me feel and not more about how it is, the book was ok, even enjoyable sometimes, but not as much as I wanted to.

Title: The Seven Husbands of Evelyn Hugo

My Review:
Oh boy, I finally finished this.

I didn't take much to finish, reading this book was almost all I did this week, but i was too curious to know how it ended. Evelyn always left you wanting for more, and I was really hooked on it.

Evelyn narrations were, unarguably, the best. Not going to lie, sometimes Monique's part of the made stop reading, or read too fast to get them over with. I liked how she applied what she learned from Evelyn to her life, but, compared to Evelyn, her life was too boring.

[major spoiler alert] I'm not quite sure I liked how Monique was related to Evelyn. It was way too obvious it was through Monique's dad, but I don't know... felt like it wasn't good enough, kind of random. It was nice to see that Monique's mom relationship with him was a parallel to Evelyn's with Harry.

Something I really liked about this book was how Evelyn explored her sexuality. From seeing it to a tool to get something from it, to something she loved to enjoy with the love of her life.

[spoiler] The last part of the book, when Evelyn was already retired and with Celia, was just ok... some parts were nice but I already accepted she wouldn't be seeing Celia again. I loved their relationship, but I was kind of done by the last bit of the book tbh... still, I really liked Celia and both she and Evelyn had some points.

Evelyn wasn't perfect, that's the whole point of the book and that's what she wants us to know, so of course this left me a bit of a bitter taste once I finished it, since it was the first time in a while when I wasn't rooting for the main character, but I really enjoyed reading this and would probably give it a re-read someday.

4.25?/5

Title: Lemonade Mouth Puckers Up
Author: Mark Peter Hughes
My Review:
Just finished reading and I have mixed feelings. I enjoyed it, most of the time, but there's a lot of stuff that I didn't liked too.

I think my biggest problem with the book is how ambitious it is, there's a lot of new characters and new experiences, but not enough pages to develop them correctly. Take Rajeev for example, I loved the idea of Mo getting to meet someone that could relate to her experiences, but in just a few pages they leave that behind to make him Stella's romantic interest! In my opinion, she didn't needed one, and I couldn't buy that either, I don't think it was explained enough how important Rajeev was to Lemonade Mouth. When he left, it definitely didn't feel like a part of Lemonade Mouth leaving, but it did feel like a very good character that I liked leaving.

I also disliked the amount of anticipation phrases there were in the book (Like, "We didn't know how much [blank] would affect us later") and Charlie's three years later povs. At first I'd die to know what happened, but by the tenth time i was kinda done.

At last, the thing I enjoyed the most about Lemonade Mouth is how normal they just are. Just kids in highschool playing in a band. This book changed that, for nothing to ever happen. Not even the event that has been mentioned since the start of the book, Sista Slash's concert, happened for them. It was a bit annoying.

But on the bright side, let's talk about the things I liked.

I really liked Charlie's new narrations and the explanation of why it changed. It's really hard for me to imagine stuff so I enjoyed everytime Charlie narrated since it made everything easier.

I also loved Wen in this book. He used to be my least favorite character, just because I liked the others more, but in this book he showed how caring he is and how much he grew from the first book. His relationship with Olivia was probably my favorite part of the book.

I wish they would've spent more time on Ray. It was interesting to see how he lived and how he interacted with Lemonade Mouth when he realized he was safe.

Would I recommend reading it if you liked the first one? Yes. Not because of what happens in the book, but to see how much the characters grew since the first book. I still prefer the first one by a lot, but I still liked this one.

2.5/5

The Boy with the Cuckoo-Clock Heart is the first book I read with love as the main plot. It was weird, but in a good way, and the descriptions were beautiful.

It was kind of a tough start for me, specially with this being my first love book. I didn't really know where the plot was going or where the climax would be. I definitely got confused when they got together, but weirdly, that's when the book really starts going. The beginning of the end is when the book really started getting my attention, I finished it quickly once everything started going wrong.

The last chapter was interesting. I liked how Méliès made a book about Jack's story, just like he said, but I'm not really sure I liked that he wasn't in the final chapter. He was a really good character and introducing a new one at the end was just . meh. The epilogue wasn't really necessary for me so I'll stay with the last chapter's ending which was really good to me.

In conclusion, 3/5. Good reading, I liked it. Might read it again someday.
